<font color="#FF0000">PROUD TO BE A VET</font><br>
<tt>Sat Oct  4  9:07:57 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Doc Spatz,<br><br>
I think that it all boils down to one thing: you wish that you had gone to Vietnam. <br><br>
I have mentioned many times on this site that I respect the opinions of those who protested the war. Way back in December, in my first post to this site, I even said that I thought the war was wrong.<br><br>
The veterans who served in Vietnam have read my posts and have shown a great deal of tolerance for my position. Not agreement, but tolerance - with maybe even a bit of understanding thrown in.<br><br>
Cook quoted Art in an earlier post in which Art explained how returning vets were victimized by &quot;extraordinarily ignorant people&quot;. My way of handling ignorance, is to pay it no heed. Too bad that so many vets were unable to sort out sincere, well meant protests against the war from the thoughtless insults that came from &quot;ignorant&quot; assholes. I think that this is where Cook and some of the others are coming from. I tried my best to show that there was a difference. That there were those protestors who had the ability to separate the warrior from the war - the soldier who answered the call; from the war that was perceived as unjust.<br><br>
Why did I go to this trouble? Simply because it bothers me to see dialogue that took place in 1970 reoccurring in 1997. The namecalling especially bothers me. <br><br>
The highest goal, in my opinion, is to aspire to become a peacemaker. In order bring two sides together, one must put himself in a precarious position - even if the risk is alienation from the group (the hyena pack). Yes, I consider myself one of *THEM*. My reason for going out on a limb has been because of the truth I saw in protesting the war and the truth in serving our country. Others I have known who served in Vietnam, though certainly not all, would agree that they saw things, be it ticket punching, or civilian abuse, that *deserved* to be protested. I know what the truth is. I was there. <br><br>
The problem arises when people, such as you, take it upon themselves to become MODERATORS who want to control discussion and dialogue. It is very revealing of your character when you blame others because certain people no longer post here. You fail to see how your own posts affect others in a negative way.<br><br>
My brother vets tolerate me and at times allow me to exchange in some light hearted teasing and banter. This is soothing to me. Despite my position on the war I am, and always will be, one of them (the hyena pack). This says alot about my brother vets.<br><br>
Where are your fellow protestors? Many made entries on this site during its inception. Where are they now? Maybe they feel as if they made their points and felt it was time to move on? Or maybe they didn't share the need to belong as you feel.<br><br>
This last post of yours is a culmination of a year's worth of attempts by you to become *like* us. It was not enough for you to be ONE of us - which at one time, you were. Art V playfully called you an FNG, remember? What happened to you? <br><br>
You can never be LIKE us because of the decision you made many years ago. A decision that I respect, regardless of whether or not you respect the decision I made.<br><br>

<p><code>-- wingman#greene.xtn.net  (Tom Dier) </code><p>


